initial_story: in recent years, classical convolutional neural networks (cnns) have beenapplied for image recognition successfully. quantum convolutional neuralnetworks (qcnns) are proposed as a novel generalization to cnns by usingquantum mechanisms. the quantum mechanisms lead to an efficient trainingprocess in qcnns by reducing the size of input from $n$ to $log_2n$. this paperimplements and compares both cnns and qcnns by testing losses and predictionaccuracy on three commonly used datasets. the datasets include the mnisthand-written digits, fashion mnist and cat/dog face images. additionally, dataaugmentation (da), a technique commonly used in cnns to improve the performanceof classification by generating similar images based on original inputs, isalso implemented in qcnns. surprisingly, the results showed that dataaugmentation didn't improve qcnns performance. the reasons and logic behindthis result are discussed, hoping to expand our understanding of quantummachine learning theory.
stories: In recent years, natural language processing (NLP) techniques have been applied to sentiment analysis with remarkable success. Generative adversarial networks (GANs) are proposed as a novel generalization to recurrent neural networks (RNNs) by using linguistic mechanisms. The linguistic mechanisms lead to an efficient training process in GANs by reducing the complexity of input from $n$ to $log_2n$. This paper implements and compares both RNNs and GANs by testing losses and prediction accuracy on three commonly used datasets. The datasets include the IMDB movie reviews, Yelp reviews, and Twitter sentiment analysis. Additionally, transfer learning (TL), a technique commonly used in RNNs to improve the performance of classification by leveraging pre-trained models, is also implemented in GANs. surprisingly, the results showed that transfer learning didn't improve GANs performance. The reasons and logic behind this result are discussed, hoping to expand our understanding of linguistic machine learning theory.

In the realm of computer vision, attention mechanisms have revolutionized object detection and image segmentation. Inspired by this breakthrough, this paper proposes a novel approach to facial expression recognition using generative adversarial networks (GANs) with linguistic guidance. By leveraging linguistic patterns to facilitate feature extraction, GANs are capable of distinguishing subtle facial expressions with unprecedented accuracy. The proposed approach is evaluated on three benchmark datasets, including the FER2013, RAF-DB, and CK+ datasets, and demonstrates significant improvements over traditional convolutional neural networks (CNNs). Furthermore, an investigation into the transferability of linguistic features to non-linguistic computer vision tasks is conducted, revealing intriguing insights into the shared principles governing human language and visual perception.

In the realm of natural language processing, contextualized word embeddings have transformed text classification and sentiment analysis. Inspired by this breakthrough, this paper proposes a novel approach to music genre recognition using recurrent neural networks (RNNs) with audio spectral guidance. By leveraging audio patterns to facilitate feature extraction, RNNs are capable of distinguishing subtle musical nuances with unprecedented accuracy. The proposed approach is evaluated on three benchmark datasets, including the MagnaTagATune, Million Song, and Million Song Dataset, and demonstrates significant improvements over traditional convolutional neural networks (CNNs). Furthermore, an investigation into the transferability of audio features to non-auditory music information retrieval tasks is conducted, revealing intriguing insights into the shared principles governing human perception and cognition.
